Write a function that reverses only the alphabetic letters in a string, 
while keeping all non-letter characters in their original positions. 
# Letters = only [Aâ€“Z, aâ€“z] 
# Digits, hyphens (-), punctuation, spaces, and s
pecial characters should stay exactly where they are 
# Case must remain unchanged (uppercase stays uppercase, lowercase stays lowercase) 
# You cannot remove characters and insert them again arbitrarily â€” 
the relative positions of non-letters must remain unchanged 
# input "a-bC-dEf-ghIj" 
# output "j-Ih-gfE-dCba"


ðŸ’¡ Idea (clean + interview-friendly)

Convert string to an array (so we can modify characters)

Use two pointers:

left starts from beginning

right starts from end

Move pointers until they point to alphabetic characters only

Swap letters

Never move or touch non-letters (-, digits, spaces, symbols, etc.)

Case stays intact automatically because we swap actual characters

Time: O(n)
Space: O(n) (string â†’ array)



âœ… Ruby Implementation
def reverse_only_letters(s)
  chars = s.chars
  left = 0
  right = chars.length - 1

  while left < right
    if chars[left] !~ /[A-Za-z]/
      left += 1
    elsif chars[right] !~ /[A-Za-z]/
      right -= 1
    else
      chars[left], chars[right] = chars[right], chars[left]
      left += 1
      right -= 1
    end
  end

  chars.join
end

ðŸ§ª Example
input  = "a-bC-dEf-ghIj"
output = reverse_only_letters(input)

puts output
# => "j-Ih-gfE-dCba"

ðŸ§  Why this is a good interview answer

âœ” No extra arrays for letters

âœ” Non-letters never move

âœ” Case preserved naturally

âœ” Linear time

âœ” Clear pointer logic (easy to explain)

